https://ific.org/publications/other/driupdateom.cfm?renderforprint=1).  The RDA was first published in 1941 by the  Food and Nutrition Board (FNB) of the National Academy of Sciences.  Since that time, the US Department of  Agriculture (USDA) and the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) have provided  significant input into their revision and development.  However, the RDA was developed for the average  person, and was designed to avoid nutritional deficiencies in the general  population, especially in school-age children.   Since 1993, the FNB has completely revised the RDA, which is now a single  component of the Dietary Reference Intake (DRI).  DRIs include information about upper  tolerance levels of intake as well as required intake.  Some vitamins and minerals, selenium and  vitamin E for example, are toxic at high levels.
